Sovereignty
---
- Types:
	- Legal
		- Unrestricted legal authority, based in Parliament
	- Political
		- Unchallenged political power, exercised by the people at election time (only temporary)
- Limits to parliamentary sovereignty:
	- Is Parliament Sovereign?
		- Could it really take power away from SP or WA?
		- EU Membership had eroded sovereignty as EU law took precedence
		- Greater use of referendums and the elections of new legislative bodies has reduced power of parliament
		- Pressure Groups/NATO/EU/Multi-national corporations erode parliament sovereignty - governments can't act as they like
	- ***BUT**
		- Parliament remains sovereign as it repealed the 1972 European Communities Act - Brexit
		- However it can't legislate to repeal against the powers of multinational corporations
- Is parliament still sovereign?
	- Monarch
		- technically has final say in passing a bill into law (royal assent). However, power not used since 1714
	- Commons
		- most influential branch which has ultimate power in making laws
	- Lords
		- Is deliberative and revising chamber. Has the power to delay legislation, e.g. hunting with dogs

- Sovereignty
	- What does sovereign mean?
		- To have ultimate political and legal power - to have supreme independent authority
	- Why is parliament said to be omnicompetent
		- As it can make any law it wishes without restriction
	- Why does parliamentary sovereignty prevent an entrenched written constitution
		- Parliament is not bound by its predecessors nor can it bind its successors. This means all existing or future laws can be amended or repealed. Thus, it is impossible for any entrenched law or constitution to exist
	- What does political sovereignty mean?
		- Refers not to the strict and clear legal definition of where power lies but where it lies in reality i.e. the practical location of power rather it's theoretical
	- What is the sovereignty of the majority part?
		- The idea that parliamentary sovereignty is really sovereignty of the majority party as the majority party has an electoral mandate to carry out it's manifesto
	- When would parliament block government plans?
		- Only when a government is abusing its mandate and acting far beyond its manifesto commitments
	- What reserve powers does parliament hold and what are their significance
		- It can block legislation and in exceptional circumstances pass a vote of no confidence in the government. This means that parliament does hold ultimate authority, despite an erosion of its power in recent years.
	- Why is the location of political sovereignty not clear-cut
		- Because it lies with the people at election time, with the government between elections, but with the proviso that parliament can ultimately overrule the government

- How to become an MP
	- Join a party
	- Get placed on the party's approved central list of candidates
	- Get nominated as the prospective parliamentary candidate (PPC) for a constituency by being elected by the local party members
	- When an election is called, ensure you are nominated by at least ten local residents and registered with the constituency's returning officer
	- Win a plurality of votes in the constituency when a general election is held
- How to become a lord
	- Nominated, either by current party leader, the House of Lords Appointments Commission or the public
	- Nominees are considered and vetted by the independent House of Lords Appointments Commission and the names are then passed to the Prime Minister.
